{"title_page": "Faysal Sohail", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Faysal A. Sohail\n| image       = Faysal-Sohail.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = Faysal Sohail\n| birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1963}}\n| birth_place = [[Al Khobar]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| residence   = [[Hillsborough, California]], USA\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]]\n| occupation  = -[[Managing Director]], [[Presidio Partners]]<br />-[[Vice Chair of the Board]], [[Silicon Valley Education Foundation]]<br />-[[Entrepreneur]]<br />-[[Venture Capitalist]]\n| spouse            = Shazia Sohail\n| children          = 4\n}}\n'''Faysal A. Sohail''' (born December 1963) is an [[United States|American]] [[venture capitalist]] and Managing Director at [[Presidio Partners]] in [[San Francisco]].  Sohail was a co-founder of Silicon Architects and on the founding team of [[Actel]] Corporation, two influential companies in the computer chip industry.<ref name=\"investing.businessweek\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121012125500/http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=513876&privcapId=19713&previousCapId=1635261&previousTitle=Evolution%20Robotics%20Inc Faysal A. Sohail]. investing.businessweek.com</ref>  Sohail serves as [[Vice Chair of the Board]] of the [[Silicon Valley Education Foundation]].<ref name=\"svefoundation\">[http://svefoundation.org/svefoundation/whoweare/faysal.php SVEF | Board of Directors \u2014 Faysal Sohail] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830082445/http://svefoundation.org/svefoundation/whoweare/faysal.php |date=August 30, 2011 }}. Svefoundation.org. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref> He is on the board of US based battery R&D company Wildcat Technology Discoveries<ref>http://www.wildcatdiscovery.com/company/board/faysal-sohail/</ref>.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSohail was born in [[Al Khobar]], [[Saudi Arabia]] to Rashid Sohail and Anjam Sohail.  Rashid Sohail, his father, was a prominent executive with Saudi Aramco in the Dhahran office, a position he held for nearly 30 years.  Anjam Sohail, his mother, is the elder sister of deceased nuclear scientist, Dr [[Mujaddid Ahmad Ijaz]].  Sohail attended high school both in Saudi Arabia and the U.S. including [[The Miller School of Albemarle]] in Virginia.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>  Sohail attended the [[University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]], where he earned his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Computer Engineering]] in 1985 and was a James Scholar.<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\">[http://web.awrcorp.com/Usa/Company/Board-Members/Faysal-Sohail/ AWR Corporation | AWR is the Innovation Leader in High-Frequency EDA]. Web.awrcorp.com. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\nHe also took graduate classes at [[Stanford University]] and consulted for Professor Abbas El Gamal at Stanford.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n==Early career==\nSohail spent his early career working in [[integrated circuit]] (IC) design engineering and marketing at [[LSI Corporation]] and Actel Corporation<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\"/>  During Sohail\u2019s tenure, Actel developed breakthrough technology in the form of [[field-programmable gate array]] (FPGA) semiconductor chips.  FPGA technology enabled creation of electronic products at a low cost, and to be reconfigured in the field when needed as opposed to sending them to a manufacturer for fabrication.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2003/08/04/smallb3.html|title=The sky's the limit for Actel chips in planned European satellites|author=Hamm, Andrew W.|date=July 31, 2003}}</ref>  Development of this technology revolutionized the chip market and created a worldwide $3 billion industry. In 1990 Sohail co-founded Silicon Architects,<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite news| url=https://blogs.forbes.com/people/fsohail/ | work=Forbes | first=Faysal | last=Sohail}}</ref> a company that pioneered the complex [[Structured ASIC]] (application-specific integrated circuits) Methodology<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=34337 Silicon Architects: Private Company Information \u2013 Businessweek]. Investing.businessweek.com (May 10, 1995). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref> called Cell-Based Array (CBA).   The ASIC architecture was considered the new design technology of choice to develop very complex ASICs for cutting-edge applications such as multimedia, graphics and telecommunications.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1995_May_24/ai_16943575/ | work=Business Wire | title=Silicon Architects Group of Synopsys Discloses Partnerships; Top ASIC Suppliers and Systems Houses Join to Forge New Design Technology Standard For Highly-Complex ICs of Late '90s | year=1995}}</ref>\nSilicon Architects was one of the first [[Silicon intellectual property]] companies.  They designed the fundamentals of computer chips, creating a platform on which companies could build chips with higher performance that used lower power, and then licensed the technology.\n[[Synopsys Inc.]] acquired Silicon Architects in 1995.  Sohail worked for Synopsys as Senior Vice President of the Intellectual Property group and then as Senior Vice President of Corporate Strategy.<ref name=\"investing.businessweek\"/>\n\nIn 1999, Sohail became CEO of [[Cadabra Design Automation]] and oversaw its acquisition by [[Numerical Technologies]] where he served as Senior Vice President of Worldwide Field Operations.<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\"/>  Cadabra Design Automation is known for providing automated transistor layout (ATL) tools to enable the manufacturing of newer, smaller chips, dramatically increasing their functionality, density and productivity.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120311142009/http://ecat.pcbcafe.com/corpprofile.php?vendor_id=1000251 Cadabra Design Automation, Inc. (acquired by Synopsys)]. pcbcafe.com</ref>\n\n==CMEA Capital==\nSohail joined CMEA Capital as Managing Director in 2002.<ref name=\"forbes\"/>  CMEA is a [[venture capital firm]] focused on life sciences, high technology, and energy & materials investments.  Founded in 1989, CMEA has been an early stage investor in many [[Silicon Valley]] high technology companies, including [[Flextronics]], Magma, [[Maxygen]], [[Monogram Biosciences]], Silicon Spice, [[Symyx]], and Syrrx.<ref>[http://www.thefunded.com/funds/partner/3787?name=Faysal+Sohail Faysal Sohail, Managing Director at CMEA Ventures]. TheFunded.com. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\n\nWhile at CMEA, Sohail helped raise and deploy over $400 million while managing over $1 billion in assets.<ref>[http://www.techconnect.org/news/press/item.html?id=85 CMEA Ventures Raises . Retrieved on January 26, 2014. 00 Million Seventh Fund. Techconnect.org (March 27, 2008). Retrieved on 2014-01-26.]</ref> CMEA led investment in [[Applied Wave Research]] (AWR), a software company that develops microwave/RF design tools for high speed systems and Integrated Circuits; and [[A123 Systems]], the largest [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in the U.S. in 2009.<ref>[http://gigaom.com/cleantech/a123systems-was-officially-the-largest-ipo-of-2009/ A123Systems Was Officially the Largest IPO of 2009 \u2014 Tech News and Analysis]. Gigaom.com (January 3, 2010). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>  A123 Systems developed groundbreaking battery technology that enabled safer, higher power batteries for use in electric cars, and is one of the leading [[lithium-ion battery]] manufacturing companies in the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/globalcleantech100/profiles-1-10 | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=MIC: 100 list A-Z (microsite) | date=September 8, 2009}}</ref>\n \nSohail served on the College of Engineering Advisory Board (CEAB) at his alma mater, the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign.  He also sits on the Board of AWR Corporation,<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\"/> AirTight Networks, Danotek Motions Technologies, [[Evolution Robotics]], and MultiGiG, Inc.,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110901065312/http://www.usrts.org/speakers-Faysal-Sohail.html Global Technology Symposium Silicon Valley]. usrts.org</ref> Solaria, IndoUS Venture Partners,<ref name=\"investing.businessweek\"/> and previously served on the Board of Directors of [[Alien Technology]].<ref>[http://nextbigfuture.com/2008/11/interview-with-faysal-sohail-managing.html Interview with Faysal Sohail, Managing Director of CMEA Ventures on Robotics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011113558/http://nextbigfuture.com/2008/11/interview-with-faysal-sohail-managing.html |date=October 11, 2011 }}. Nextbigfuture.com (November 1, 2008). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nFaysal is a board member of the American Pakistan Foundation (APF), an organization co-founded by [[Hillary Clinton]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Sec. Hillary Clinton Mentions APF in Speech at Global Diaspora Forum, May 2011|url=http://www.americanpakistan.org/news/sec-hillary-clinton-mentions-apf-speech-global-diaspora-forum-may-2011|publisher=American Pakistani Foundation|accessdate=May 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304133613/http://www.americanpakistan.org/news/sec-hillary-clinton-mentions-apf-speech-global-diaspora-forum-may-2011|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> in order to \"effectively catalyze long-term economic development and social change in Pakistan\".<ref>{{cite web|title=American Pakistan Foundation announces new appointments to Board of Directors|url=http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs060/1102707682012/archive/1108669705857.html|accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nSohail is Chairman of the Board of the Silicon Valley Education Foundation, a nonprofit organization that joins business and community leaders to improve public education in Silicon Valley and increase the number of college-bound and prepared students in the area.<ref>[http://www.knightfoundation.org/news/press_room/knight_press_releases/detail.dot?id=241197 New Silicon Valley Education Foundation Launched] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616063236/http://knightfoundation.org/news/press_room/knight_press_releases/detail.dot?id=241197 |date=June 16, 2010 }}. Knight Foundation (February 4, 2008). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>  The Foundation focuses on advancing student performance in math and science in [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]] school districts.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n===Global Entrepreneurship===\nIn 2010, Sohail accompanied then [[California]] [[Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] to [[Moscow]] to meet with Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] to encourage entrepreneurial investments and share his thoughts and experience in financing innovation.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101023220257/http://www.bsr-russia.com/en/innovation/item/1003-russia-needs-entrepreneur-role-models.html Russia needs entrepreneur role models]. bsr-russia.com. October 18, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.themoscowtimes.com/business/article/role-models-needed-to-spur-innovation/420405.html 'Role Models' Needed to Spur Innovation | Business]. The Moscow Times. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-15/medvedev-needs-role-models-to-spur-innovation-in-russia-cmea-capital-says.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Lucian | last=Kim | title=Medvedev Needs Role Models to Spur Innovation in Russia, CMEA Capital Says | date=October 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSohail was chosen as one of 11 delegates for the [[U.S. Department of State]]\u2019s [[Global Entrepreneurship Program]], created to promote entrepreneurship around the world.  The delegation was focused on growing entrepreneurship and building relationships in the [[Middle East]]/[[North Africa]], particularly in [[Egypt]].<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/156390.pdf THE GLOBAL ENTREPRENEURSHIP PROGRAM. Egypt Entrepreneurship Delegation, Cairo, Egypt, January 9\u201312, 2011]. state.gov</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2011, the US Jakarta-Indonesia Embassy issued a press release naming Sohail as one of 13 members of an Entrepreneurship Delegation set to visit Indonesia July 19\u201324, 2011. According to the press release, \"The Entrepreneurship Delegation will enhance U.S. and Indonesian efforts to promote entrepreneurship and strengthen business ties...\u201d <ref>{{cite web|title=Promoting Entrepreneurship Between The U.S. And Indonesia: American and Indonesian business leaders inspire local startups|url=http://jakarta.usembassy.gov/pr_06152011.html|work=June 15 Press Release|accessdate=June 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621232241/http://jakarta.usembassy.gov/pr_06152011.html|archivedate=June 21, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSohail is also a Charter Member of OPEN in Silicon Valley, an organization committed to promoting  entrepreneurship and business leadership in the Pakistani-American community.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n==Recognition==\nSohail was named the 2011 Pioneer Business Leader by the Silicon Valley Education Foundation. This award is given to business leaders who have contributed to the improvement of education in the Silicon Valley.  Previous awardees include [[John Chambers (CEO)|John Chambers]], chairman and [[CEO]] of [[Cisco]].\n\n==Personal life==\nSohail lives in [[Hillsborough, California]] with his wife Shazia Sohail and four children Sikander, Sabrina, Zaineb and Dania.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*http://www.presidiopartners.com/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20151116131424/http://www.airtightnetworks.com/\n*http://www.cmea.com/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20110430020618/http://www.svefoundation.org/svefoundation/\n*http://www.opensiliconvalley.org/\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sohail, Faysal}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Silicon Valley people]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:American Ahmadis]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:People from Hillsborough, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Faysal A. Sohail\n| image       = Faysal-Sohail.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = Faysal Sohail\n| birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1963}}\n| birth_place = [[Al Khobar]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| residence   = [[Hillsborough, California]], USA\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]]\n| occupation  = -[[Managing Director]], [[Presidio Partners]]<br />-[[Vice Chair of the Board]], [[Silicon Valley Education Foundation]]<br />-[[Entrepreneur]]<br />-[[Venture Capitalist]]\n| spouse            = Shazia Sohail\n| children          = 4\n}}\n'''Faysal A. Sohail''' (born December 1963) is an [[United States|American]] [[venture capitalist]] and Managing Director at [[Presidio Partners]] in [[San Francisco]].  Sohail was a co-founder of Silicon Architects and on the founding team of [[Actel]] Corporation, two influential companies in the computer chip industry.<ref name=\"investing.businessweek\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20121012125500/http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=513876&privcapId=19713&previousCapId=1635261&previousTitle=Evolution%20Robotics%20Inc Faysal A. Sohail]. investing.businessweek.com</ref>  Sohail serves as [[Vice Chair of the Board]] of the [[Silicon Valley Education Foundation]].<ref name=\"svefoundation\">[http://svefoundation.org/svefoundation/whoweare/faysal.php SVEF | Board of Directors \u2014 Faysal Sohail] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830082445/http://svefoundation.org/svefoundation/whoweare/faysal.php |date=August 30, 2011 }}. Svefoundation.org. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSohail was born in [[Al Khobar]], [[Saudi Arabia]] to Rashid Sohail and Anjam Sohail.  Rashid Sohail, his father, was a prominent executive with Saudi Aramco in the Dhahran office, a position he held for nearly 30 years.  Anjam Sohail, his mother, is the elder sister of deceased nuclear scientist, Dr [[Mujaddid Ahmad Ijaz]].  Sohail attended high school both in Saudi Arabia and the U.S. including [[The Miller School of Albemarle]] in Virginia.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>  Sohail attended the [[University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]], where he earned his [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Computer Engineering]] in 1985 and was a James Scholar.<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\">[http://web.awrcorp.com/Usa/Company/Board-Members/Faysal-Sohail/ AWR Corporation | AWR is the Innovation Leader in High-Frequency EDA]. Web.awrcorp.com. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\nHe also took graduate classes at [[Stanford University]] and consulted for Professor Abbas El Gamal at Stanford.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n==Early career==\nSohail spent his early career working in [[integrated circuit]] (IC) design engineering and marketing at [[LSI Corporation]] and Actel Corporation<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\"/>  During Sohail\u2019s tenure, Actel developed breakthrough technology in the form of [[field-programmable gate array]] (FPGA) semiconductor chips.  FPGA technology enabled creation of electronic products at a low cost, and to be reconfigured in the field when needed as opposed to sending them to a manufacturer for fabrication.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2003/08/04/smallb3.html|title=The sky's the limit for Actel chips in planned European satellites|author=Hamm, Andrew W.|date=July 31, 2003}}</ref>  Development of this technology revolutionized the chip market and created a worldwide $3 billion industry. In 1990 Sohail co-founded Silicon Architects,<ref name=\"forbes\">{{cite news| url=https://blogs.forbes.com/people/fsohail/ | work=Forbes | first=Faysal | last=Sohail}}</ref> a company that pioneered the complex [[Structured ASIC]] (application-specific integrated circuits) Methodology<ref>[http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=34337 Silicon Architects: Private Company Information \u2013 Businessweek]. Investing.businessweek.com (May 10, 1995). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref> called Cell-Based Array (CBA).   The ASIC architecture was considered the new design technology of choice to develop very complex ASICs for cutting-edge applications such as multimedia, graphics and telecommunications.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1995_May_24/ai_16943575/ | work=Business Wire | title=Silicon Architects Group of Synopsys Discloses Partnerships; Top ASIC Suppliers and Systems Houses Join to Forge New Design Technology Standard For Highly-Complex ICs of Late '90s | year=1995}}</ref>\nSilicon Architects was one of the first [[Silicon intellectual property]] companies.  They designed the fundamentals of computer chips, creating a platform on which companies could build chips with higher performance that used lower power, and then licensed the technology.\n[[Synopsys Inc.]] acquired Silicon Architects in 1995.  Sohail worked for Synopsys as Senior Vice President of the Intellectual Property group and then as Senior Vice President of Corporate Strategy.<ref name=\"investing.businessweek\"/>\n\nIn 1999, Sohail became CEO of [[Cadabra Design Automation]] and oversaw its acquisition by [[Numerical Technologies]] where he served as Senior Vice President of Worldwide Field Operations.<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\"/>  Cadabra Design Automation is known for providing automated transistor layout (ATL) tools to enable the manufacturing of newer, smaller chips, dramatically increasing their functionality, density and productivity.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120311142009/http://ecat.pcbcafe.com/corpprofile.php?vendor_id=1000251 Cadabra Design Automation, Inc. (acquired by Synopsys)]. pcbcafe.com</ref>\n\n==CMEA Capital==\nSohail joined CMEA Capital as Managing Director in 2002.<ref name=\"forbes\"/>  CMEA is a [[venture capital firm]] focused on life sciences, high technology, and energy & materials investments.  Founded in 1989, CMEA has been an early stage investor in many [[Silicon Valley]] high technology companies, including [[Flextronics]], Magma, [[Maxygen]], [[Monogram Biosciences]], Silicon Spice, [[Symyx]], and Syrrx.<ref>[http://www.thefunded.com/funds/partner/3787?name=Faysal+Sohail Faysal Sohail, Managing Director at CMEA Ventures]. TheFunded.com. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\n\nWhile at CMEA, Sohail helped raise and deploy over $400 million while managing over $1 billion in assets.<ref>[http://www.techconnect.org/news/press/item.html?id=85 CMEA Ventures Raises . Retrieved on January 26, 2014. 00 Million Seventh Fund. Techconnect.org (March 27, 2008). Retrieved on 2014-01-26.]</ref> CMEA led investment in [[Applied Wave Research]] (AWR), a software company that develops microwave/RF design tools for high speed systems and Integrated Circuits; and [[A123 Systems]], the largest [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in the U.S. in 2009.<ref>[http://gigaom.com/cleantech/a123systems-was-officially-the-largest-ipo-of-2009/ A123Systems Was Officially the Largest IPO of 2009 \u2014 Tech News and Analysis]. Gigaom.com (January 3, 2010). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>  A123 Systems developed groundbreaking battery technology that enabled safer, higher power batteries for use in electric cars, and is one of the leading [[lithium-ion battery]] manufacturing companies in the world.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/globalcleantech100/profiles-1-10 | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=MIC: 100 list A-Z (microsite) | date=September 8, 2009}}</ref>\n \nSohail served on the College of Engineering Advisory Board (CEAB) at his alma mater, the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign.  He also sits on the Board of AWR Corporation,<ref name=\"web.awrcorp\"/> AirTight Networks, Danotek Motions Technologies, [[Evolution Robotics]], and MultiGiG, Inc.,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110901065312/http://www.usrts.org/speakers-Faysal-Sohail.html Global Technology Symposium Silicon Valley]. usrts.org</ref> Solaria, IndoUS Venture Partners,<ref name=\"investing.businessweek\"/> and previously served on the Board of Directors of [[Alien Technology]].<ref>[http://nextbigfuture.com/2008/11/interview-with-faysal-sohail-managing.html Interview with Faysal Sohail, Managing Director of CMEA Ventures on Robotics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111011113558/http://nextbigfuture.com/2008/11/interview-with-faysal-sohail-managing.html |date=October 11, 2011 }}. Nextbigfuture.com (November 1, 2008). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nFaysal is a board member of the American Pakistan Foundation (APF), an organization co-founded by [[Hillary Clinton]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Sec. Hillary Clinton Mentions APF in Speech at Global Diaspora Forum, May 2011|url=http://www.americanpakistan.org/news/sec-hillary-clinton-mentions-apf-speech-global-diaspora-forum-may-2011|publisher=American Pakistani Foundation|accessdate=May 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304133613/http://www.americanpakistan.org/news/sec-hillary-clinton-mentions-apf-speech-global-diaspora-forum-may-2011|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> in order to \"effectively catalyze long-term economic development and social change in Pakistan\".<ref>{{cite web|title=American Pakistan Foundation announces new appointments to Board of Directors|url=http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs060/1102707682012/archive/1108669705857.html|accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nSohail is Chairman of the Board of the Silicon Valley Education Foundation, a nonprofit organization that joins business and community leaders to improve public education in Silicon Valley and increase the number of college-bound and prepared students in the area.<ref>[http://www.knightfoundation.org/news/press_room/knight_press_releases/detail.dot?id=241197 New Silicon Valley Education Foundation Launched] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616063236/http://knightfoundation.org/news/press_room/knight_press_releases/detail.dot?id=241197 |date=June 16, 2010 }}. Knight Foundation (February 4, 2008). Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref>  The Foundation focuses on advancing student performance in math and science in [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]] school districts.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n===Global Entrepreneurship===\nIn 2010, Sohail accompanied then [[California]] [[Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] to [[Moscow]] to meet with Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] to encourage entrepreneurial investments and share his thoughts and experience in financing innovation.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101023220257/http://www.bsr-russia.com/en/innovation/item/1003-russia-needs-entrepreneur-role-models.html Russia needs entrepreneur role models]. bsr-russia.com. October 18, 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.themoscowtimes.com/business/article/role-models-needed-to-spur-innovation/420405.html 'Role Models' Needed to Spur Innovation | Business]. The Moscow Times. Retrieved on January 26, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-15/medvedev-needs-role-models-to-spur-innovation-in-russia-cmea-capital-says.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Lucian | last=Kim | title=Medvedev Needs Role Models to Spur Innovation in Russia, CMEA Capital Says | date=October 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\nSohail was chosen as one of 11 delegates for the [[U.S. Department of State]]\u2019s [[Global Entrepreneurship Program]], created to promote entrepreneurship around the world.  The delegation was focused on growing entrepreneurship and building relationships in the [[Middle East]]/[[North Africa]], particularly in [[Egypt]].<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/156390.pdf THE GLOBAL ENTREPRENEURSHIP PROGRAM. Egypt Entrepreneurship Delegation, Cairo, Egypt, January 9\u201312, 2011]. state.gov</ref>\n\nOn June 15, 2011, the US Jakarta-Indonesia Embassy issued a press release naming Sohail as one of 13 members of an Entrepreneurship Delegation set to visit Indonesia July 19\u201324, 2011. According to the press release, \"The Entrepreneurship Delegation will enhance U.S. and Indonesian efforts to promote entrepreneurship and strengthen business ties...\u201d <ref>{{cite web|title=Promoting Entrepreneurship Between The U.S. And Indonesia: American and Indonesian business leaders inspire local startups|url=http://jakarta.usembassy.gov/pr_06152011.html|work=June 15 Press Release|accessdate=June 20, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621232241/http://jakarta.usembassy.gov/pr_06152011.html|archivedate=June 21, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nSohail is also a Charter Member of OPEN in Silicon Valley, an organization committed to promoting  entrepreneurship and business leadership in the Pakistani-American community.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n==Recognition==\nSohail was named the 2011 Pioneer Business Leader by the Silicon Valley Education Foundation. This award is given to business leaders who have contributed to the improvement of education in the Silicon Valley.  Previous awardees include [[John Chambers (CEO)|John Chambers]], chairman and [[CEO]] of [[Cisco]].\n\n==Personal life==\nSohail lives in [[Hillsborough, California]] with his wife Shazia Sohail and four children Sikander, Sabrina, Zaineb and Dania.<ref name=\"svefoundation\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*http://www.presidiopartners.com/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20151116131424/http://www.airtightnetworks.com/\n*http://www.cmea.com/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20110430020618/http://www.svefoundation.org/svefoundation/\n*http://www.opensiliconvalley.org/\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sohail, Faysal}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Silicon Valley people]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign alumni]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:American Ahmadis]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:People from Hillsborough, California]]\n", "name_user": "EasterSun", "label": "safe", "comment": "Inserted additional role", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faysal_Sohail"}
