the [[South Island Line]], built on the old site of [[Wong Chuk Hang Estate]]. It is named after [[Wong Chuk Hang|the locality of the same name]] and serves residents in that area, as well as connect to a public transport interchange on a widened section of Heung Yip Road. A network of footbridges serves future commercial and residential areas, and the station exists as a hub to the Shum Wan region as a whole. The station opened on 28 December 2016<ref name=\"rthk20161205\">{{cite web| title=MTR's South Island Line to open on December 28 |url=http://news.rthk.hk/rthk/en/component/k2/1300460-20161205.htm |publisher=[[RTHK]] |date=5 December 2016 }}</ref> with the rest of the South Island Line. The South Island Line depot is located to the south.\n==History==\nWong Chuk Hang station was opened on 28 December 2016.\n==Station layout==\n\n{|cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|-\n|style=\"width:50px;border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;vertical-align:top;\" rowspan=3|'''U2<br /> Platforms'''\n|style=\"width:100px;border-top:solid 1px gray;\"|Platform <span style=\"color:#{{rcr|MTR|South Island}};\">'''2'''</span>\n|style=\"width:450px;border-top:solid 1px gray;\"|{{0|\u2192}} {{rcb|MTR|South Island|yes}} towards [[Admiralty Station (MTR)|Admiralty]] <small>([[Ocean Park station (MTR)|Ocean Park]])</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Island platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Platform <span style=\"color:#{{rcr|MTR|South Island}};\">'''1'''</span>\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|\u2190 {{rcb|MTR|South Island|yes}} towards [[South Horizons Station|South Horizons]] <small>([[Lei Tung Station|Lei Tung]])</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;vertical-align:top;\" rowspan=2|'''U1'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" rowspan=2|Concourse\n|Customer service, MTRShops\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Footbridges\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;vertical-align:top;\" rowspan=2|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Street level\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Exits, public transport interchange\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Depot\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\"|Wong Chuk Hang Depot\n|}\nThis elevated station has two tracks and an [[island platform]].<ref name=\":1\"/> Commissioned by the [[MTR Corporation]], [[Aedas]], as part of the engineering team led by [[Atkins (company)|Atkins]], were the architect for the station.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.aecom.com/deployedfiles/Internet/Geographies/Asia/Asia%20News/Spectrum_2nd%20issue-20110506.pdf|title=Spectrum Asia Issue 02/April 2011|publisher=AECOM}}</ref>\n\nThe station artwork, ''Huddle'' by Chao Harn-kae, resembles birds flying.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr-southislandline.hk/en/information/WCH.html|title=MTR \u2013 South Island Line > Station Information > Wong Chuk Hang Station|website=mtr-southislandline.hk|access-date=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr12-13/chinese/panels/tp/tp_rdp/papers/tp_rdp0104cb1-379-2-ec.pdf#page=43 |script-title=zh:\u6e2f\u9435\u8eca\u7ad9\u85dd\u8853\u8a08\u5283\u53ca\u9032\u5c55 |trans-title=Approach and Updates of MTR Art Programme|date=January 2013|publisher=[[Legislative Council of Hong Kong|Government of Hong Kong]]|pages=43\u201344|access-date=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Entrances/exits===\nA footbridge connection to various areas of Shum Wan is provided.<ref name=\":1\" /> An exit also connects the station to the planned Wong Chuk Hang Station Public Transport Interchange, for passengers to connect to other modes of public transport.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr-southislandline.hk/pdf/meeting/district/ppt25-1.pdf|title=Southern District Council Meeting 16 May 2013|date=16 May 2013|website=|publisher=[[MTR Corporation]]|page=37|access-date=1 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nWong Chuk Hang Station has three entrances/exits. Exit B is subdivided into 3 exits and entrances.<ref name=\":0\" /> The footbridge across Wong Chuk Hang Road and Heung Yip Road, connecting the B-prefixed exits, opened on 3 April 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr-southislandline.hk/pdf/en/notice/MTR_Notice_WCH_Footbridge_U-turn_PC_20160329_en.pdf|title=Notice: South Island Line (East) Project \u2013 Opening of Wong Chuk Hang Footbridge, U-turn and Pedestrian Crossings on Wong Chuk Hang Road|last=Siu|first=Samantha|date=29 March 2016|website=|publisher=[[MTR Corporation]]|access-date=1 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n* '''A1/A2''': Public transport interchange in median of Heung Yip Road {{Access icon|15px|Wheelchair user access}}<ref name=\":0\" /> (1 lift)<ref name=\":1\" />\n* '''B''': Nam Long Shan Road, Wong Chuk Hang Road, [[Aberdeen, Hong Kong|Aberdeen]], [[Wong Chuk Hang]] industrial area, Yip Kan Street, Yip Hing Street (via footbridge) {{Access icon|15px|Wheelchair user access}} (3 lifts)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{ multiple image | direction = vertical | align = right | width = 800\n| image1 = Footbridge of Wong Chuk Hang Station entrance and exit B (panorama, blue sky).jpg | caption1 = <center>Exit B footbridge</center>\n}}\n\n== Wong Chuk Hang Depot ==\nWhile the main station will take up the northern part of the former Wong Chuk Hang Estate site, an underground depot is located to the south. This depot services and maintains South Island Line trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/eng/projects/sileia/index.php/WCH|title=MTR > South Island Line (East) > Environmental Impact Assessment|date=August 2010|website=mtr.com.hk|publisher=[[MTR Corporation]]|access-date=2 November 2016}}</ref> The depot is completely sealed and is situated on sunken ground to avoid noise pollution to areas nearby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/eng/projects/sileia/index.php/WCH/noise|title=MTR > South Island Line (East) > Environmental Impact Assessment|date=August 2010|website=mtr.com.hk|publisher=[[MTR Corporation]]|access-date=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAtop the depot, a residential estate will be developed by the [[MTRC]]. It will comprise 14 blocks with about 4,700 flats, as well as a commercial element.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wong Chuk Hang Station|url=http://www.mtr.com.hk/en/corporate/properties/sil_wongchukhang.html|publisher=MTR Corporation}}</ref>\n\n==Future==\nWong Chuk Hang Station is proposed to be an interchange station between the eastern and western sections of the South Island Line. The platforms of the [[South Island Line (West)]] will be built over those of the South Island Line.\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{South Island Line navbox}}\n{{South Island Line (West) navbox}}\n{{Southern District, Hong Kong}}\n[[Category:MTR stations on Hong Kong Island]]\n[[Category:South Island line]]\n[[Category:South Island line (West)]]\n[[Category:Wong Chuk Hang]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromSouth Island LinetoSouth Island lineusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wong_Chuk_Hang_station"}
{"title_page": "Edward Francis Blewitt", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = \n| office = Member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] from the 22nd District\n| termstart = 1907\n| termend = 1909\n| successor = [[Walter McNichols]]\n| predecessor = [[Jacob Gilbert Zern]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date = January 2, 1859\n| birth_place = [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], U.S.\n| relations = [[Joe Biden]] (great-grandson)\n| death_date = May 26, 1926 (aged 67)\n| death_place = [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Edward Francis Blewitt''' (January 2, 1859 {{En dash}} May 26, 1926) was an American politician who served as a member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lafayette.edu/about/?p=29444|title=Vice President Joe Biden Discusses American Innovation|author=Gehman, Geoff|date=May 3, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202110137/http://www.lafayette.edu/about/?p=29444&wpmp_switcher=mobile|archivedate=February 2, 2014|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Lafayette College]]}}</ref> With his first wife, Mary Ellen Stanton, he was the maternal great-grandfather of [[Joe Biden]], 47th [[Vice President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scrantontimes.com/articles/2008/08/24/news/sc_times_trib.20080824.a.pg1.tt24biden_s1.1896121_top4.txt|title=Remembering his roots|author=Krawczeniuk, Borys|date=August 24, 2008|newspaper=[[The Times-Tribune (Scranton)|The Times-Tribune]]|accessdate=January 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406014842/http://www.scrantontimes.com/articles/2008/08/24/news/sc_times_trib.20080824.a.pg1.tt24biden_s1.1896121_top4.txt|archivedate=April 6, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=os8wAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA644&lpg=PA644&dq=%22Miss+Mary+E.+Stanton,+was+born+in+Scranton%22&source=bl&ots=IHv8FLmojz&sig=ACfU3U0QmNdwHBtggl5IBuoU13YcBWwIaA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjCiObMjOjoAhVba80KHRlxCY0Q6AEwAHoECAAQAQ]</ref><ref>https://ancestornetwork.ie/how-vice-president-joe-biden-traced-his-irish-ancestry/</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBlewitt was born in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], the son of Catherine (Scanlon) and Patrick Blewitt, who were Irish emigrants, from Rappagh, Ballina.<ref>https://www.con-telegraph.ie/news/roundup/articles/2016/05/11/4119572-us-vice-president-to-visit-mayo-in-june/</ref> Blewitt attended [[Lafayette College]], served as class president, and graduated as a [[Civil engineering|civil engineer]] in 1879.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/MemBio.cfm?ID=5076&body=S|title=Edward F Blewett|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=English|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 1883 until 1893, Blewitt was the [[Municipal engineering|City Engineer]] of [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. He later was a consulting engineer and chief engineer of [[Guadalajara]], [[Mexico]]. In 1883, Blewitt was elected to one term as a school controller.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V08DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA77&dq=edward+blewitt+senator#v=onepage&q=edward%20blewitt%20senator&f=false|title=Who's who in Pennsylvania: A Biographical Dictionary of Contemporaries|date=1908|language=en}}</ref> In 1906, Blewitt was elected to the State Senate representing [[Lackawanna County, Pennsylvania]], serving from 1907 to 1909.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/serRes.cfm?search&body=S&dist=22|title=Historical Biographies|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=English|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> Upon his election to the [[Pennsylvania legislature]], Blewitt became one of the first Roman Catholics to serve in public office in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishfamilyhistorycentre.com/article/vice-president-joe-bidens-irish-family-history-1|title=Vice President Joe Biden's Irish Family History|website=Irish Family History Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Om0CAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT161&lpg=PT161&dq=Edward+F+Blewett&source=bl&ots=sKnN6O4Nw6&sig=ACfU3U2din4oimRaZw2nsVAoTzuO0NWL1A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimnYTaiPHhAhUCOK0KHXxuBhA4ChDoATANegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=Edward%20F%20Blewett&f=false|title=Obama\u2019s Irish Roots|last=Murray|first=Gabriel|date=2012-10-19|publisher=Youcanprint|isbn=9788867517220|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBlewitt was the co-founder of the [[Friendly Sons of St. Patrick]] in Scranton in 1908.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://goballycastle.com/BidenIrishRoots.html|title=Biden\u2019s Irish Roots|website=goballycastle.com|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}{{Pennsylvania-PASenate-stub}}\n\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania State Senator stubs]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Democrats]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania state senators]]\n[[Category:1926 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Lafayette College alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New Orleans]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = \n| office = Member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]] from the 22nd District\n| termstart = 1907\n| termend = 1909\n| successor = [[Walter McNichols]]\n| predecessor = [[Jacob Gilbert Zern]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date = January 2, 1859\n| birth_place = [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], U.S.\n| relations = [[Joe Biden]] (great-grandson)\n| death_date = May 26, 1926 (aged 67)\n| death_place = [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Edward Francis Blewitt''' (January 2, 1859 {{En dash}} May 26, 1926) was an American politician who served as a member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lafayette.edu/about/?p=29444|title=Vice President Joe Biden Discusses American Innovation|author=Gehman, Geoff|date=May 3, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202110137/http://www.lafayette.edu/about/?p=29444&wpmp_switcher=mobile|archivedate=February 2, 2014|url-status=dead|publisher=[[Lafayette College]]}}</ref> He is the maternal great-grandfather of [[Joe Biden]], 47th [[Vice President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scrantontimes.com/articles/2008/08/24/news/sc_times_trib.20080824.a.pg1.tt24biden_s1.1896121_top4.txt|title=Remembering his roots|author=Krawczeniuk, Borys|date=August 24, 2008|newspaper=[[The Times-Tribune (Scranton)|The Times-Tribune]]|accessdate=January 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406014842/http://www.scrantontimes.com/articles/2008/08/24/news/sc_times_trib.20080824.a.pg1.tt24biden_s1.1896121_top4.txt|archivedate=April 6, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> With his first wife, Mary Ellen Stanton, he was the great-grandfather of U.S. Vice President [[Joe Biden]].<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=os8wAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA644&lpg=PA644&dq=%22Miss+Mary+E.+Stanton,+was+born+in+Scranton%22&source=bl&ots=IHv8FLmojz&sig=ACfU3U0QmNdwHBtggl5IBuoU13YcBWwIaA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjCiObMjOjoAhVba80KHRlxCY0Q6AEwAHoECAAQAQ]</ref><ref>https://ancestornetwork.ie/how-vice-president-joe-biden-traced-his-irish-ancestry/</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBlewitt was born in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]], the son of Catherine (Scanlon) and Patrick Blewitt, who were Irish emigrants, from Rappagh, Ballina.<ref>https://www.con-telegraph.ie/news/roundup/articles/2016/05/11/4119572-us-vice-president-to-visit-mayo-in-june/</ref> Blewitt attended [[Lafayette College]], served as class president, and graduated as a [[Civil engineering|civil engineer]] in 1879.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/MemBio.cfm?ID=5076&body=S|title=Edward F Blewett|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=English|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nFrom 1883 until 1893, Blewitt was the [[Municipal engineering|City Engineer]] of [[Scranton, Pennsylvania]]. He later was a consulting engineer and chief engineer of [[Guadalajara]], [[Mexico]]. In 1883, Blewitt was elected to one term as a school controller.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V08DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA77&dq=edward+blewitt+senator#v=onepage&q=edward%20blewitt%20senator&f=false|title=Who's who in Pennsylvania: A Biographical Dictionary of Contemporaries|date=1908|language=en}}</ref> In 1906, Blewitt was elected to the State Senate representing [[Lackawanna County, Pennsylvania]], serving from 1907 to 1909.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/serRes.cfm?search&body=S&dist=22|title=Historical Biographies|website=The official website for the Pennsylvania General Assembly.|language=English|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref> Upon his election to the [[Pennsylvania legislature]], Blewitt became one of the first Roman Catholics to serve in public office in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishfamilyhistorycentre.com/article/vice-president-joe-bidens-irish-family-history-1|title=Vice President Joe Biden's Irish Family History|website=Irish Family History Centre|language=en|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Om0CAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT161&lpg=PT161&dq=Edward+F+Blewett&source=bl&ots=sKnN6O4Nw6&sig=ACfU3U2din4oimRaZw2nsVAoTzuO0NWL1A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimnYTaiPHhAhUCOK0KHXxuBhA4ChDoATANegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=Edward%20F%20Blewett&f=false|title=Obama\u2019s Irish Roots|last=Murray|first=Gabriel|date=2012-10-19|publisher=Youcanprint|isbn=9788867517220|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBlewitt was the co-founder of the [[Friendly Sons of St. Patrick]] in Scranton in 1908.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://goballycastle.com/BidenIrishRoots.html|title=Biden\u2019s Irish Roots|website=goballycastle.com|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}{{Pennsylvania-PASenate-stub}}\n\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:1859 births]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania State Senator stubs]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Democrats]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania state senators]]\n[[Category:1926 deaths]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Scranton, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American civil engineers]]\n[[Category:Lafayette College alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from New Orleans]]\n", "name_user": "All Hallow's Wraith", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Francis_Blewitt"}
{"title_page": "Septicflesh", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Septicflesh\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               = Septicflesh With Full Force 2018 10.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| caption             = Septicflesh at [[With Full Force]] 2018\n| origin              = [[Athens]], Greece\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Symphonic death metal]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2014/05/16/septicflesh-may-yet-enter-golden-age-titan/|title=Septicflesh May Yet Enter the Golden Age With Their Titan|publisher=[[MetalSucks]]|date=May 16, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2015}}</ref>|[[death-doom]] (early)}}\n| years_active        = 1990\u20132003, 2007\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n*[[Karmageddon Media|Hammerheart]]\n*[[Season of Mist]]\n*[[Prosthetic Records|Prosthetic]]\n*[[Nuclear Blast]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = {{flatlist|\n*[[Chaostar]]\n*[[Firewind]]\n*[[Nightfall (band)|Nightfall]]\n*[[Nightrage]]\n*[[Rotting Christ]]\n*[[Defect Designer]]\n}}\n| website             = {{url|www.septicflesh.com}}\n| current_members     = \n*Sotiris Vayenas\n*[[Spiros Antoniou|Spiros \"Seth\" Antoniou]]\n*Christos Antoniou\n*[[Kerim Lechner|Kerim \"Krimh\" Lechner]]\n| past_members        = \n*Akis \"Lethe\" Kapranos\n*Kostas Savvidis\n*George \"Magus Wampyr Daoloth\" Zaharopoulos\n*Fotis Benardo\n*Alexander Haritakis\n*[[Bob Katsionis]]\n}}\n\n'''Septicflesh''' (formerly known as '''Septic Flesh''') are a Greek [[death metal]] band from [[Athens]], founded in 1990.<ref name=\"AMG\"/>\n\n== History ==\n\nSepticflesh were formed in Athens in March 1990 by Sotiris Vayenas (guitar), Spiros Antoniou (bass and vocals), and Christos Antoniou (guitars). They released a debut [[Extended play|EP]], ''Temple of the Lost Race'' in December with Black Power Records, 1991.<ref name=\"AMG\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p554912|pure_url=yes}}|title=Septic Flesh > Biography|last=True|first=Chris|work=Allmusic|publisher=Macrovision Corporation|accessdate=December 11, 2008}}</ref> The band recorded their first full-length album, ''[[Mystic Places of Dawn]]'', in April 1994 at the Storm studio with the co-production of Magus Wampyr Daoloth (who had been the keyboardist for [[Rotting Christ]]).<ref name=\"SFBIO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abstrata.net/sfsite/bio.html|title=Time Catcher|publisher=Septicflesh|accessdate=December 11, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121083856/http://www.abstrata.net/sfsite/bio.html|archivedate=November 21, 2008}}</ref> released by [[Holy Records]]. They started working on a new album for 1995 and named it ''[[Esoptron]]''. It was produced by Septic Flesh and George Zacharopoulos, recorded and mixed at Storm Studios in March - April 1995, mastered by Sonic Contact (France), and released by [[Holy Records]]\n\nSession vocalist Natalie Rassoulis joined for ''[[The Ophidian Wheel]]'' (1997) and again for ''[[A Fallen Temple]]'' (1998).<ref name=\"MEMB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abstrata.net/sfsite/bio.html|title=Time Catcher|publisher=Septicflesh|accessdate=April 18, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121083856/http://www.abstrata.net/sfsite/bio.html|archivedate=November 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe group split up in October 2003, and after the breakup, its members moved on to different or existing projects:\nChris Antoniou continued involvement with [[Chaostar]], which he formed in 1998, and Katsionis played guitar for [[Nightfall (band)|Nightfall]] and keyboards for [[Firewind]].\nTheDevilWorx formed a year after Septic Flesh's disbanding, and featured some members\nfrom Septic Flesh's original line-up. In March 2007, guitarist Sotiris Vayenas revealed his plans for a new solo project called Aenaos.\n\nOn February 19, 2007, Septic Flesh announced a reunion for Greece's ''Metal Healing Festival'' featuring [[Orphaned Land]], [[Rage (German band)|Rage]] and [[Aborted]], set to take place July 20\u201322.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=67373|title=Septic Flesh to Reunite for Greece's Metal Healing Festival|publisher=Blabbermouth.Net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930225236/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=67373|archivedate=September 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Septicflesh 003.jpg|thumb|left|Christos Antoniou (2015)]]\nOn April 3, 2007, [[Blabbermouth|Blabbermouth.net]] reported the band reunited for a seventh full-length CD, for French record label [[Season of Mist]]. According to guitarist and composer Christos Antoniou, the release would feature a full orchestra and a choir, totalling 80 musicians and 32 singers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=69817|title=Reunited Septic Flesh to Record New Album for Season of Mist|publisher=Blabbermouth.net}}</ref> Septic Flesh finalized the new album, ''Communion'', in Studio Fredman in Sweden; it was released in April 2008. By this time the band had changed its name from Septic Flesh to Septicflesh. According to guitarist Christos it looks better and states a new phase in the band.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lordsofmetal.nl/showinterview.php?id=2095&lang=en|title=Lords of Metal ezine|author=Roel de Haan|work=Lords of Metal}}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2009, the band announced that they had begun work on a new studio album, tentatively planned for release in the beginning of 2011.\n\nOn December 17, 2010, the band released the first single, \"The Vampire From Nazareth\", and announced that the new album will be shipped on April 28 in the UK, and April 29 in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/septicfleshband/blog/541246438|title=Featured Content on Myspace|work=Myspace}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=126731|title=SEPTICFLESH Hard At Work On New Material|publisher=Blabbermouth.Net}}</ref>\n\nOn February 12, 2014, the band released details about ''[[Titan (album)|Titan]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metalcallout.com/news/septicflesh-titan-new-album-details.html|title=Septicflesh 'Titan' New Album Details|publisher=Metal CallOut}}</ref> The album was released in June 2014. On December 15, 2014, it was announced that [[Kerim Lechner|Kerim \"Krimh\" Lechner]] had joined Septicflesh as their new drummer, following the recent departure of their former longtime drummer, Fotis Benardo (a.k.a. Fotis Gianakopoulos).\n\nIn June 2016 interview it was declared that, since early 2016, Septicflesh had been working on their tenth studio album, scheduled for release toward spring 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/latest-news/septicflesh-begins-work-on-a-new-album-with-ex-decapitated-drummer|title=SEPTICFLESH Begins Work On A New Album With Ex-DECAPITATED Drummer - Metal Injection|author=|date=June 7, 2016|website=Metalinjection.net|accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/events/news_comments.php?news_id=30473|title=Septicflesh - New Album Update, Coming In 2017 - Metal Storm|author=|date=|website=Metalstorm.net|accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/septicflesh-begins-work-on-new-album-2017-release-planned|title=SEPTICFLESH Begins Work On New Album; 2017 Release Planned|website=Bravewords.com|accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://metalholic.com/septicflesh-begin-work-new-album-2017-release-planned/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 21, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202082418/http://metalholic.com/septicflesh-begin-work-new-album-2017-release-planned/ |archivedate=February 2, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.season-of-mist.com/news/septicflesh-2016-06-08|title=Septicflesh News: SEPTICFLESH - Season of Mist, Metal Label|author=|date=|website=Season-of-mist.com|accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref> In early June 2017, band members claimed that Septicflesh's tenth album, titled ''[[Codex omega|Codex Omega]]'', is officially due to release on September 1, 2017. Like the previous album, ''Titan'', ''Codex Omega'' was released through [[Prosthetic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/septicflesh-to-codex-omega-album-in-september/|title=SEPTICFLESH To Release 'Codex Omega' Album In September|author=|date=June 14, 2017|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe band signed to Nuclear Blast Records.\n\n==Personnel==\n<gallery perrow=\"3\" caption=\"Septicflesh, live at [[With Full Force]] 2018\" widths=\"180\" heights=\"180\">\nSepticflesh With Full Force 2018 06.jpg|Singer and Bassist Spiros Antoniou\nSepticflesh With Full Force 2018 09.jpg|Lead guitarist Christos Antoniou\nSepticflesh With Full Force 2018 03.jpg|Tour guitarist Dinon Prassas \n</gallery>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Current members'''\n*[[Spiros Antoniou|Spiros \"Seth Siro Anton\" Antoniou]] \u2013 [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[Bass guitar|bass]] <small>(1990\u20132003, 2007\u2013present)</small>\n*Sotiris Vayenas \u2013 rhythm guitar, clean vocals, [[Keyboard instrument|keyboard]]s <small>(1990\u20132003, 2007\u2013present)</small>\n*Christos Antoniou \u2013 lead guitar, orchestrations, [[Sampler (musical instrument)|samples]] <small>(1990\u20132003, 2007\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Kerim Lechner|Kerim \"Krimh\" Lechner]] \u2013 drums <small>(2014\u2013present)</small>\n\n{{col-2}}\n'''Former members'''\n*Dimitris Valasopoulos \u2013 drums <small>(1990\u20131991)</small>\n*Akis \"Lethe\" Kapranos \u2013 drums <small>(1999\u20132003)</small>\n*George \"Magus Wampyr Daoloth\" Zaharopoulos \u2013 keyboards <small>(2001\u20132003)</small>\n*Fotis Gianakopoulos \u2013 drums <small>(2003, 2007\u20132014)</small>\n\n'''Session musicians'''\n*Kostas Savvidis \u2013 drums <small>(1993\u20131997)</small>\n*[[Bob Katsionis]] \u2013 keyboards <small>(2003)</small>\n*Dinos \"Psychon\" Prassas - Touring guitar <small>(2008\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:110 bottom:120 top:0 right:0\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/03/1990 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom\nScaleMajor = increment:5 start:1991\nScaleminor = increment:1 start:1992\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:4\n\nColors =\n  id:Vocals  value:red         legend:Lead_vocals\n  id:Lead    value:teal        legend:Lead_guitar\n  id:Rhythm  value:green       legend:Rhythm_guitar,_clean_vocals\n  id:Bass    value:blue        legend:Bass\n  id:Drums   value:orange      legend:Drums\n  id:Keys    value:purple      legend:Keyboards\n  id:studio  value:black       legend:Studio_album\n \nLineData =\n layer:back color:studio\n  at:21/05/1994\n  at:18/07/1995\n  at:20/02/1997\n  at:09/03/1998\n  at:15/11/1999\n  at:18/02/2003\n  at:17/03/2008\n  at:18/04/2011\n  at:20/06/2014\n  at:01/09/2017\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Spiros   text:\"Spiros Antoniou\"\n  bar:Christos text:\"Christos Antoniou\"\n  bar:Sotiris  text:\"Sotiris Vayenas\"\n  bar:George   text:\"George Zaharopoulos\"\n  bar:Dimitris  text:\"Dimitris Valasopoulos\"\n  bar:Akis     text:\"Akis Kapranos\"\n  bar:Fotis    text:\"Fotis Gianakopoulos\"\n  bar:Krimh    text:\"Kerim Lechner\"\n\nPlotData=\n  width:11\n  bar:Spiros      from:01/03/1990 till:21/11/2003   color:Vocals\n  bar:Spiros      from:19/02/2007 till:end          color:Vocals\n  bar:Spiros      from:01/03/1990 till:21/11/2003   color:Bass width:3\n  bar:Spiros      from:19/02/2007 till:end          color:Bass width:3\n  ba